<DOC><DOCNO> AP881013-0290 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-13-88 0222EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-HollyFarms-Tyson Bjt   10-13 0598</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Holly Farms-Tyson, Bjt,0616</SECOND><HEAD>Tyson Must Sweeten Pot To Buy Holly Farms, Analysts Say</HEAD><DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Tyson Foods Inc. may have to sweeten its$891 million buyout offer before Memphis-based Holly Farms Corp.gives in to the bid from its rival poultry processor.   Holly Farms officials on Wednesday would say only that they wereconsidering Tyson's offer of $45 cash and a quarter share of itsClass A common stock for each of Holly Farms' 18.1 millionoutstanding shares.   Tyson, of Springdale, Ark., is the nation's largest poultryprocessor. A Holly Farms buyout would increase Tyson's market sharefrom 18 percent to 28 percent, analysts said.   ``I think Holly Farms will sell to Tyson only as a lastresort,'' said John M. McMillin, an analyst with Prudential-BacheSecurities in New York.   McMillin said he valued Holly Farms at $55 a share or more. Hesaid the Tyson offer amounts to about $49.25 a share.   ``If Tyson wants to buy the company he's going to have to pay$55,'' McMillin said.   Holly Farms stock rose sharply in heavy trading, jumping $6.62{a share to $49.62{ in composite New York Stock Exchange trading.Tyson fell 62{ cents a share to $17 in over-the-counter trading.   Based on Wednesday's closing price, Tyson's offer would be worth$49.25 a share, or about $891.4 million.   Holly Farms officials could not be reached for comment Wednesdaynight.   McMillin also speculated Holly Farms alternatively would pursuea leveraged buyout by managers who will seek to take the companyprivate.   ``There's a couple of options,'' McMillin said. ``One is to lookfor a white knight, which could potentially be a Phillip Morris ora Sara Lee...look for a company to basically choose who they wantto get married to.   ``The other is to pursue a management-led leveraged buyout, takethe company private. I think that's what they're pursuing rightnow,'' McMillin said.   John Lawrence, an associate analyst for Morgan Keegan inMemphis, said he believes Holly Farms could be bought out by Tysonat a price in the range of $50 to $55 a share.   Hours before Tyson announced its offer late Tuesday, Holly Farmsannounced it had been approached by an unidentified companyregarding a possible business combination. Holly Farms said nospecific proposal had been received and the company did not intendto seek one.   The company also said it had activated a shareholder rightsplan, commonly known as a ``poison pill'' takeover defense, aimedat making a hostile takeover prohibitively expensive.   ``We haven't heard a word. We are just waiting on whateverdecision they are making over there. We are standing by,'' BobJustice of Tyson Foods said Wednesday. ``We do have a timetable ofOct. 19. That's our deadline. Hopefully, they can make a decisionprior to that. And we feel optimistic about a response beforethat.''   Officials of the two companies met four weeks ago in Memphis.Tyson asked for access to nonpublic corporate information fromHolly Farms to help determine whether a higher offer was warranted.   Tyson, which posted sales of about $1.8 billion last year,produces 14 million pounds of chicken meat each week from anoperation that includes hatcheries, feed mills, processing plantsand a sophisticated marketing arm. The company sells both wholechickens and ``value enhanced products'' to supermarkets, fast foodchains and institutional customers.   Holly Farms is a diversified foods company, with about 50percent of its sales concentrated in chicken. The company, whichalso mills flour and provides other meats for the food serviceindustry, had sales of about $1.6 billion last year.</TEXT></DOC>